Reasoning: The workbook has a single sheet "Sheet1". Row 11 contains the header with the company name in column A and the list of countries in columns B‑G, followed by a column “No of countries” in column I (the target column). Rows 12 and 13 contain employee counts for companies ABC and EFG respectively. The task is to place a formula in cells I12 and I13 that counts how many of the country columns (B‑G) have a value > 0 for that row.

The appropriate Excel formula that works in LibreOffice is:
`=SUMPRODUCT(--(B12:G12>0))`
and similarly for row 13:
`=SUMPRODUCT(--(B13:G13>0))`

We will:
1. Load the workbook.
2. Write these formulas into I12 and I13.
3. Save the workbook to the output directory with the same filename.
4. Call `recalculate` to evaluate the formulas.
5. Verify the computed values by re‑loading the file with `data_only=True` and printing I12 and I13.
Code:
```repl
import pathlib, openpyxl
from openpyxl.utils import column_index_from_string
from openpyxl import load_workbook

# Paths
input_path = pathlib.Path("/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_12307_init.xlsx")
output_dir = pathlib.Path("/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/")
output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
output_path = output_dir / input_path.name

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = load_workbook(input_path, data_only=False)
ws = wb.active  # only one sheet

# Write formulas into I12 and I13
ws["I12"] = "=SUMPRODUCT(--(B12:G12>0))"
ws["I13"] = "=SUMPRODUCT(--(B13:G13>0))"

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Recalculate formulas
calc_result = await recalculate(str(output_path))
print("Recalculate result:", calc_result)

# Reload with data_only to see evaluated values
wb2 = load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
ws2 = wb2.active
print("I12 evaluated:", ws2["I12"].value)
print("I13 evaluated:", ws2["I13"].value)
```
2026-04-14 07:30:01,724 INFO RLM iteration 3/50
Reasoning: The previous formula `=SUMPRODUCT(--(B12:G12>0))` evaluated to 0, likely due to LibreOffice compatibility issues with the double‑unary operator. A more reliable LibreOffice‑compatible formula for counting cells greater than zero is `COUNTIF`. We will replace the formulas in I12 and I13 with `=COUNTIF(B12:G12,">0")` and `=COUNTIF(B13:G13,">0")` respectively, then recalculate and verify the results.
Code:
```repl
import pathlib, openpyxl
from openpyxl import load_workbook

# Paths
input_path = pathlib.Path("/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_12307_init.xlsx")
output_dir = pathlib.Path("/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/")
output_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
output_path = output_dir / input_path.name

# Load workbook (preserve formulas)
wb = load_workbook(input_path, data_only=False)
ws = wb.active  # only one sheet

# Write LibreOffice‑compatible COUNTIF formulas
ws["I12"] = '=COUNTIF(B12:G12,">0")'
ws["I13"] = '=COUNTIF(B13:G13,">0")'

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Recalculate formulas
calc_result = await recalculate(str(output_path))
print("Recalculate result:", calc_result)

# Reload with data_only to see evaluated values
wb2 = load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
ws2 = wb2.active
print("I12 evaluated:", ws2["I12"].value)
print("I13 evaluated:", ws2["I13"].value)
```
